attributes.title: Qualcomm: A Buy On Fundamentals And Technicals Alike
summary: Qualcomm fundamentals are unimpressive on the topline, but cash flow is prodigious, meaning leverage is falling.
Valuation multiples are unchallenging for buyers at present.
Technically we believe the stock may be lining up for a move up.

Never Mind The Growth, Look At The Cashflow!

We've written Qualcomm (NASDAQ:QCOM) stock up three times on these pages of late. Here's how those calls went so far.

March 2022 - A Stink Buy

July 2022 - A Righteous Sell

February 2023 - A Thus-Far Unsuccessful Hold

If for some reason you had decided to hang on our every word and do exactly as those notes suggested with no modification or tradecraft on your part (always unwise), thus far you would have lost 24% buying the thing in March 2022, gained 24% shorting the name in July 2022, and lost 15% had you simply held it from February. So let's call the first two a wash and consider this a 15% net stink call thus far. Not our finest hour, but 15% isn't irrecoverable in this name in our view.

The company reported its Q4 of FY9/23 Wednesday after the close. So where does it stand now?

Well, we believe it to be buy-able and we rate the stock at Accumulate. And here's why.

Qualcomm Stock - Fundamental Analysis And Valuation

Here are the numbers up to and including this quarter just printed.

Revenue isn't pretty - still in decline (-24% this quarter, and -19% on a TTM basis). And accounting earnings, which we measure using EBITDA, also aren't so hot. TTM EBITDA of $12bn is way down from the recent TTM high of $20bn struck as recently as the September 2022 quarter.

Where things get more interesting is cash flow, leverage, and valuation multiples.

TTM unlevered pretax free cash flow stands at $11.4bn right now, which (1) is more or less the same as EBITDA, telling you that the EBITDA is high quality earnings, and (2) a recent high - only the June 2021 quarter came close to that mark.

As a result of all this cash generation, net leverage now sits at just 0.3x TTM EBITDA, down from 0.6x only two quarters back.

And valuation sits at just 11.7x TTM UFCF, 11.0x TTM EBITDA or 3.7x TTM revenue. They aren't big multiples.

The company is guiding to flat growth for Q1 of FY9/24 (that's the December 2023 quarter) which would be a significant milestone if achieved. And this we believe is why the stock turned up today on the print. On the face of it the story isn't so hot - but something got investors excited, and it wasn't a modest beat that did it.

Qualcomm Technical Analysis

Here's the chart as we see it.

The stock has tested and re-tested support in the region of the .618 Fibonacci retrace of the whole move up from the 2019 lows to the 2021 highs - call it $101-107/share as strong support. Support at such a retracement level is common for a Wave Two low; and if that was a Wave Two low then the next big move is likely, up.

Qualcomm Stock Rating

Based on the volume x price profile - that's the gray bars on the right hand side that indicate the price zones in which big and small volumes are traded - we rate QCOM at "Accumulate" between $105-$122/share. And we think it's capable of running up significantly from there, perhaps to prior all-time highs and beyond.

So, neither our best nor our worst calls so far, we now flag QCOM as an Accumulate opportunity - we'll see you in a quarter's time to see how this idea aged.

Cestrian Capital Research, Inc - 1 November 2023.
